if (magic != HEADER_MAGIC) {
    // Legacy Encrypt_AESGCM format: raw 12-byte IV at start
    byte[] iv = new byte[12];
    iv[0] = (byte)(magic >> 24);
    iv[1] = (byte)(magic >> 16);
    iv[2] = (byte)(magic >> 8);
    iv[3] = (byte)(magic);
    dis.readFully(iv, 4, 8);

    EncryptionMetadata metadata = new EncryptionMetadata();
    metadata.ivBase64 = Base64.getEncoder().encodeToString(iv);
    metadata.hasEmbeddedHeader = false; // ← skip header step in decrypt()
    return metadata;
}




// REPLACE this:
try (CipherInputStream cis = new CipherInputStream(is, cipher)) {
    byte[] buffer = new byte[bufferSize];
    int read;
    while ((read = cis.read(buffer)) != -1) {
        os.write(buffer, 0, read);
    }
}

// WITH this (doFinal gives you proper auth tag verification):
if (metadata.hasEmbeddedHeader) {
    skipHeader(is);
}
byte[] ciphertext = is.readAllBytes();
byte[] plaintext = cipher.doFinal(ciphertext);  // throws AEADBadTagException on bad key
os.write(plaintext);
```

> **Why:** `CipherInputStream` with AES/GCM is known to silently return garbage or no data instead of throwing on auth tag failure. `cipher.doFinal()` is the safe path.

---

### 3. `skipHeader()` — guard is already correct, nothing to change

`decrypt()` only calls `skipHeader(is)` when `metadata.hasEmbeddedHeader` is true, so legacy files naturally skip it. No change needed there — just don't move that call outside the `if` block.

---

### At a glance
```
readMetadata()   ← add legacy fallback branch
decrypt()        ← swap CipherInputStream loop → cipher.doFinal()
skipHeader()     ← no change needed
